The effect of this Ode, as following the seventh‚ is the same as that which has been noticed in the sequence of Od. 1. 11, 12, 13; 1. 37, 38. See Introd. to Odes i—iii, § 12.

1-5. Diur. points out the art which is expended in the collocation of this stanza. The point is the contrast between the little he demands, brought out by the emphatic position of ‘ ulla,' ‘umquam,' ‘ dente,' ‘ uno,’ ‘ ungui,’ and the large offer which he makeS, brought out by the single unqualified ‘ crederem,’ the equivalent, in a single word, for the whole stanzaful of offered conditions. For a similarly balanced sentence, see 3. 3. 30-33.
